description.text:
### Tested versions

Reproducible in v4.3.stable.official [77dcf97d8] and v4.4.beta.custom_build [f42e612da]

### System information

Godot v4.4.beta (f42e612da) - Windows 10 (build 19045) - Multi-window, 2 monitors - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3080 (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.6636) - AMD Ryzen 7 5800X 8-Core Processor (16 threads)

### Issue description

The normals of `SoftBody3D` objects are incorrect at runtime. When creating a cube as a soft body, lighting does not affect the `SoftBody3D` mesh correctly and this can be seen from visualizing the normals directly with the following custom shader:
```glsl
shader_type spatial;

void vertex() {
	// Called for every vertex the material is visible on.
}

void fragment() {
	// Called for every pixel the material is visible on.
	ALBEDO = vec3(abs(NORMAL.x), abs(NORMAL.y), abs(NORMAL.z));
}

//void light() {
//	// Called for every pixel for every light affecting the material.
//	// Uncomment to replace the default light processing function with this one.
//}
```

I was also thinking this might be related to using the `BoxMesh` rather than an imported custom mesh, so I created a cube in blender and imported that to godot as an `.obj`, but it also exhibits the same incorrect normals.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/0b433128-ce7b-4911-b9f0-6b394c98a2c9)

The `SoftBody3D` normals are correct in the editor:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9c7f5f4f-aaf7-48f2-bd15-bd3a06088055)


### Steps to reproduce

1. Create a `SoftBody3D`, `DirectionalLight3D`, and `Camera3D`
2. Assign the `SoftBody3D` a `BoxMesh`
3. Run the project

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[softbodytest.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/18832988/softbodytest.zip)
